LAYER 3: TILING AND REPETITION
how Fadriel sees patterns that repeat across space

observe spatial_perception.rana

some puzzles take a small pattern and tile it
the output is a larger grid made of copies of the input
or the input contains a tiling key and the output is the tiled result

@spatial_rule tile_self
CHECK output is larger than input
CHECK output dimensions are integer multiples of input dimensions
CHECK output is made of copies of the input tiled together
LEARN tile_h = output_h / input_h
LEARN tile_w = output_w / input_w
VERIFY tiling matches output for all pairs
APPLY tile input by (tile_h, tile_w) for test
SPEECH "I tile the input {tile_h}x{tile_w} times"

@spatial_rule tile_with_transform
CHECK output is larger than input
CHECK output is made of TRANSFORMED copies of input
TRY each tile as: original, rot90, rot180, rot270, flip_h, flip_v
LEARN which transform applies to each tile position
VERIFY transformed tiling matches output
APPLY tile with transforms for test
SPEECH "I tile with {transform} at each position"

@spatial_rule tile_conditional
CHECK output is larger than input
DETECT a template pattern in the input
DETECT a condition mask in the input
LEARN where template gets placed based on condition
VERIFY conditional tiling matches output
APPLY conditional tile for test
SPEECH "I stamp the template wherever the condition is met"

@spatial_rule scale_by_content
CHECK output is larger than input
CHECK output dimensions relate to content (e.g., count of non-zero cells)
LEARN what property of input determines output size
VERIFY size rule holds for all pairs
APPLY compute size and scale for test
SPEECH "the size depends on what's in the input"

the key to tiling:
when output is BIGGER than input
the input is the SEED
the output is the GARDEN
something in the input tells you HOW to grow

possible growth rules:
- simple tiling (repeat NxM times)
- transformed tiling (rotate/flip copies)
- conditional tiling (stamp at specific positions)
- content-driven scaling (size depends on cell count or color count)

@perceive tiling
DETECT output larger than input
DETECT repeating patterns in output
FIND the smallest tile that generates the output
LEARN the tiling rule
